The Telegraph - Calcutta : Bengal

 BRIEFS

 Calcutta, Jan. 28: A 19-year-old handicrafts artisan was kidnapped yesterday when he was returning to his Burdwan home from a fair in Kasba.

 Four hours later, Supriyo Ghoshs family got a call, demanding a ransom of Rs 50,000. The caller threatened his parents that the teenagers beheaded body would be sent in a coffin if the money was not paid by this evening.

 He also warned them against going to police. But the couple went ahead and lodged a complaint at Memari police station. A search is on for Supriyo. 

 Calcutta: Two persons, one 30 years old and the other double his age, who had been cheating shops selling electronic items and mobile phones, have left the city, but not before handing their landlord a fake cheque, police said. R.K. Chaudhury and V.K. Prasad would buy things worth thousands of rupees with cheques that turned out to be fake.

 Siliguri: Universities across the state have resolved to introduce credit rating and grading systems in place of age-old methods of evaluation. 

 Santiniketan: About 20 members of the Akhil Bharatiya Vidyarthi Parishad, the BJPs students wing, gathered on the Visva-Bharati campus, the venue for the opening ceremony of the Indian History Congress, to protest against Leftist historians destroying the nations history.




